#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: bias country-label rotation toward horizontal (classroom-globe look).

Previous pipeline (worldbook_label_fit.py) chose, for every country, whichever
angle MAXIMIZED available room - so even compact, barely-elongated countries
(Canada, Mexico, Zimbabwe, Zambia...) ended up tilted 15-35deg, since some
angle nearly always offers a little more room than dead horizontal. Net result:
only 19/242 countries landed near 0deg, median |rotation| was 30deg. Real atlases
do not work this way - they print names horizontally by default and only swing
them off-axis for genuinely thin/elongated shapes (Chile, Norway, Vietnam, Japan).

This re-optimizes with a different objective: for each country, first check if
horizontal (0deg) keeps at least 80% of the span and 50% of the perpendicular
clearance that the previous best-angle placement already achieved (i.e. "would
this look about as good as what is already live, but flat"). If yes, snap to
0deg. If not, scan outward in 6deg steps (checking both directions at each step,
keeping whichever sign gives more room) and stop at the SMALLEST rotation that
clears the same 80%/50% bar, instead of the single angle that maximizes room.
Text size is never changed. A handful of countries (5: small/irregular shapes
where recomputed candidate points come up just short of their own previous bar)
fall back to their exact currently-deployed rot/span/perp, unchanged, as a safety
net - this patch can only make labels more horizontal or leave them as-is, never
worse than what is already live.

Net effect: 87/242 countries (was 19) now sit at exactly 0deg - USA, Brazil,
Russia, Switzerland, Singapore, Zimbabwe, Zambia, Luxembourg among them. Median
|rotation| drops from 30deg to 12deg. Genuinely elongated countries keep a real
tilt because they need it to stay legible inside their own borders: Chile 84deg,
Norway 42deg, Mexico -36deg, Morocco 36deg, UK -36deg, Vietnam -48deg.
Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_label_horizontal.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys, re

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

